  "reportSummary": "SENTINEL detected a combined sewer overflow event in the Thames Tideway 8 hours before Environment Agency notification. The system's predictive rainfall model flagged high CSO probability even before discharge began, then confirmed the event through progressive sensor degradation (DO drop from 7.5 to 2.5 mg/L, turbidity spike to 240 NTU) and rapid eDNA-based pathogen detection. Source attribution identified CSO discharge at 88% confidence. The Digital Biosentinel highlighted particular concern for the recovering Thames smelt population (52% mortality risk). The 8-hour lead time could have enabled earlier recreational use warnings, protecting public health.",
